How to Run a Session: The Three-Act Structure
This guide provides a clear, repeatable structure for running a single game session. It is designed to manage time effectively, give each player a moment in the spotlight, and seamlessly transition from character-focused story progression into the main, group-focused adventure. Each session can be thought of as a three-act play.
Part 1: The Opening Monologue - Setting the Scene
(Estimated Time: 5 Minutes)
Every session should begin with a short, evocative introduction delivered by you, the GM. This sets the tone, reminds players of their current situation, and grounds them in the world.
For a brand-new adventure:
Establish the Atmosphere: Describe the city or location where the adventure begins. Use sensory details from your City Profile (the smell of pine in Falkreath, the sound of canals in Riften).
Acknowledge Their Reputation: Briefly mention their most recent heroic deed. This validates their past accomplishments and explains why they might be sought after.
Present the Immediate Situation: Describe where the characters are right now (e.g., gathered in the main room of an inn, walking through the city gates).
End with a Transition: Conclude by smoothly transitioning into Part 2.
Example (Start of "Blood on the Pine"):
"The tales of your victory at Thornheart Grove have preceded you, whispers of sellswords who can handle more than just bandits. You've traveled south to the grim hold of Falkreath, a town that feels perpetually on the edge of twilight, the scent of pine and damp earth clinging to everything. You find yourselves in 'Dead Man's Drink,' where the atmosphere is thick with stale mead and nervous sweat. The inn is quiet, the patrons whispering. The stage is set. We'll now begin the Order of Business to see what each of you does with your first afternoon in this nervous town."
For a continuing adventure:
Recap the Last Session: Briefly summarize the key events and where you left off ("Last time, you defeated the vampire fledgling and found Valerius's journal, revealing his obsession with preservation...").
Describe the Immediate Aftermath: Detail the current scene based on the cliffhanger ("You now stand in the dusty library, the journal in your hands, the path to the Preservatory lying open before you...").
Reiterate the Goal: Remind them of their immediate objective ("You know the preservation ritual is nearing completion, and time is running out.").

Part 2: The Order of Business - Upkeep & Personal Arcs
(Estimated Time: 10-20 Minutes Per Player)
This is the narrative heart of your character's personal journey. Far more than simple "downtime," the Order of Business is a structured phase where the consequences of past actions catch up, personal goals are pursued, and the story of each individual hero is actively driven forward. It is the primary means through which your character's individual story unfolds.
How it Works:
The "Seize the Day" Roll: To determine the order, have every player make a standard d20 roll (no modifiers). The highest roll goes first. This represents who is quickest to act on the day's events or whose personal situation demands the most immediate attention.
The GM Frames the Scene: This is not unstructured free time. Going in order, the GM presents each player with a personalized scene based on their character's ongoing story threads, unresolved issues, or recent actions. The GM sets the stage, describing where the character is and what is happening to them.
Example 1 (A Warrior's Past): "Kaelen, after your victory at the Grove, a courier finds you. He hands you a letter bearing the tarnished seal of your estranged family. It seems word of your deeds has reached your father, and the letter is not one of congratulations. It reads..."
Example 2 (A Rogue's Debt): "Bjorn, as you're browsing the market stalls, a familiar, shifty-eyed Argonian steps out from an alley. It's Veezara, the informant you paid for that tip last week. 'The information was good, yes?' he hisses. 'But my boss is wondering when you'll be handling that other little problem we discussed...'"
Example 3 (A Mage's Discovery): "Elara, the ancient tome you recovered from the Pale Lady's tomb has been whispering to you in your sleep. This morning, as you open it, one of the runes begins to glow with a faint, cold light, and you feel a specific, magical pull towards the College of Winterhold, a sense of an unanswered question..."


Player Reaction & Resolution: The spotlight is now on the player. How do they react to the situation the GM has presented? Their choices during this scene constitute their "upkeep."
Engage the Plot: The player can deal directly with the presented story beatΓÇöreading the letter, negotiating with the informant, or researching the tome. This is how their personal story progresses.
Manage Resources: Within the context of the scene, they can perform other tasks. For example, Kaelen might crumple the letter and declare, "I need a stronger sword before I deal with my father," and then head to the smithy. This organically integrates shopping and preparation into the narrative.
Seek Allies: A player might take their problem to another party member, turning their individual scene into a brief two-person roleplaying opportunity.
The scene concludes when the player has made a clear decision or taken a decisive action that resolves the immediate situation, often leading to a new objective or a shift in their personal quest log.


Tracking the Threads (Consequence & Accumulation): The outcome of each "Order of Business" scene is not forgotten. The GM should make a note of the player's choices.
Did a relationship change? (Veezara is now impatient; Kaelen's father is now actively hostile).
Was a new lead discovered? (Elara now knows she needs a specific focusing crystal from the College).
Was a resource gained or lost? (Bjorn pays off his debt but is now low on coin).
These accumulated threads will become the basis for framing future "Order of Business" scenes, creating a rich, evolving personal narrative for each character that runs parallel to the main adventure.



Part 3: The Main Event - The Adventure Proper
(Estimated Time: The Remainder of the Session)
Once the "Order of Business" is complete, the party has had a chance to breathe, advance their personal stories, and gather information. Now, it's time for the main quest to begin.
The Transition:
The trigger for the main quest should be the final beat of the "Order of Business."
The Planned Encounter: "After you've all concluded your business, you gather back at the Bee and Barb for a meal. As you do, an impeccably dressed woman at a corner table catches your eye and gestures for you to approach."
The Direct Approach: A courier finds the party, or an NPC from a spotlight scene directly asks for their help ("Kaelen, since you are here at the temple, I must beg for your aid...").
Running the Adventure:
This is where you use your pre-planned adventure structure, like "The Pale Lady's Tomb" or "Thornheart Grove."
Follow the 5-Section Structure: Guide the players through the pre-planned beats: Guardian -> Puzzle -> Setback -> Boss -> Reward.
Focus on the Group: The spotlight now shifts from individual players to the party as a whole. Encourage teamwork and collaborative problem-solving.
Fail Forward: Remember the core GM principle. If they fail a roll, the story doesn't stop. It gets more complicated and interesting.

The Resolution & The Look Ahead
(Estimated Time: 10 minutes)
After the final boss is defeated and the treasure is claimed, end the session with a clear resolution and a hook for the future.
The Return Journey: Briefly narrate the return to the city or quest giver. Describe the change in the atmosphere now that the threat is gone.
The Payoff: Roleplay the scene where they receive their reward. The quest giver's reaction should reflect the party's performance. This is also when grateful NPCs (like rescued miners) can offer thanks or future assistance.
Award Advancement: Explicitly state: "For completing this adventure, you each gain 1 Advancement Point." This is a critical, satisfying moment for players.
The Look Ahead (The Epilogue): End the session with a final narrative beat that wraps up the current story and hints at what's next. This could be a new rumor they overhear, a mysterious note they find among the treasure, or a change in the world based on the Consequence Calendar.
Example Epilogue:
"With the Pale Lady defeated and the gratitude of Winterhold warming you better than any fire, you settle in for a well-deserved rest. As you spend your newfound coin, however, you hear a traveling merchant speak of trouble down in the Rift. He says Maven Black-Briar is hiring professionals to deal with a... corruption in the woods. It seems a hero's work is never done. We'll end the session there."


